    "recap_headline": "University of Memphis Athletics",
    "recap_text": "MEMPHIS, Tenn. \u2013\nThe University of Memphis (5-12) baseball team powered its way to a dominant 14-2 victory over Eastern Illinois (6-8) Friday evening at FedExPark Avron Fogelman Field.\nThe Tigers scored in all six innings and used a pair of four-run frames to pull away. Memphis finished the night with 12 hits, including three home runs, while holding the Panthers to just four hits in the seven-inning run-rule victory.\nWill Howell\nstarted on the mound for Memphis and earned the win, allowing one run on one hit across four innings while striking out five.\nCharlie Smith\nentered in relief and worked the final three innings to earn his first save of the season.\nThe Tigers will be back at FedExPark Avron Fogelman Field tomorrow for game two of the series. First pitch is scheduled for 2:05 p.m.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nMemphis opened the scoring in the first inning when designated hitter\nJames Smith IV\nsingled to left field to score\nFreddy Rodriguez\n, giving the Tigers a 1-0 lead.\nThe Tigers added another run in the second when catcher\nTrae Cassidy\nlifted a sacrifice fly to center field that scored\nJack Little\n.\nMemphis extended the lead in the third inning as center fielder\nMichael Gupton\ndrove in\nShane Cox\non a fielder's choice before\nWebb Watson\nplated another run with a groundout to make it 4-0.\nEastern Illinois got on the board in the fourth inning when Joey Hagen grounded out to first base, scoring Kyree Alexander to cut the deficit to 4-1.\nThe Tigers responded with a four-run fourth inning. Right fielder\nCade Hitson\ndelivered an RBI single before Watson drove in two runs with a single to right, pushing Memphis ahead 8-1.\nMemphis added four more runs in the fifth inning when\nJames Smith IV\nhit a two-run double and\nMichael Gupton\nlaunched a two-run homer to left field.\nEastern Illinois scored once in the sixth on an RBI single by Tyler Castro, but Memphis answered immediately with two home runs in the bottom half of the inning from second baseman\nJack Little\nand\nTrae Cassidy\nto extend the lead to 14-2.\nCharlie Smith\nretired the Panthers in order in the seventh to seal the run-rule victory for Memphis.\nNOTABLES\nMemphis scored at least one in every inning of the game for the first time since at least 2000.\nThe 14 total runs are the second highest total this season.\nThe Tigers drew 10 walks, the most in a game since February 25, 2025, against Alabama A&M.\nJavon Hernandez\n,\nFreddy Rodriguez\nand\nJack Little\nall stole a base for the Tigers, bringing the team's season total to 39 steals, which ranks in the top 40 nationally.\nRodriguez is 11-12 on the year while Hernandez is a perfect 8-8.\nMichael Gupton\nfinished 2-for-3 with four RBIs and a home run.\nGupton has recorded four RBIs in three of his last four games and leads the team with 22 total for the year.\nHis 369-foot homer in the fifth was his sixth of the year (most on the team) and his tenth extra-base hit of the season (tied for most on the team).\nJames Smith IV\nwent 3-for-4 with three RBIs, including a two-run double in the fifth inning.\nTied career-highs in both hits and RBIs\nWebb Watson\nadded three RBIs for the Tigers.\nJack Little\nand\nTrae Cassidy\nboth hit their first home runs of the season.\nMemphis has now had 10 different players hit a homer this year.\nAfter a double on Friday, second baseman\nShane Cox\ncontinued his streak of reaching base safely in every game thus far and continues his 10-game hitting streak.\nCox has recorded at least one hit in 16 of 17 games this season.\nCox leads the Tigers in batting average (.391), hits (27), doubles (7), and extra-base hits (10).\nWill Howell\nearned his first win of the season after allowing just one run across four innings with five strikeouts.\nCharlie Smith\nrecorded his first save of the year after pitching the final three innings.\nSCORING SUMMARY\nBottom 1:\nJames Smith IV\nsingled,\nFreddy Rodriguez\nscored.\nMemphis 1, Eastern Illinois 0\nBottom 2:\nTrae Cassidy\nhit a sacrifice fly,\nJack Little\nscored.\nMemphis 2, Eastern Illinois 0\nBottom 3:\nMichael Gupton\nreached on a fielder's choice,\nShane Cox\nscored.\nWebb Watson\ngrounded out,\nMichael Gupton\nscored.\nMemphis 4, Eastern Illinois 0\nTop 4:\nJoey Hagen grounded out, Kyree Alexander scored.\nMemphis 4, Eastern Illinois 1\nBottom 4:\nMichael Gupton\nwalked,\nTrae Cassidy\nscored.\nCade Hitson\nsingled,\nFreddy Rodriguez\nscored.\nWebb Watson\nsingled,\nJames Smith IV\nand\nMichael Gupton\nscored.\nMemphis 8, Eastern Illinois 1\nBottom 5:\nJames Smith IV\ndouble,\nFreddy Rodriguez\nand\nShane Cox\nscored.\nMichael Gupton\nhomered,\nParker Price\nscored.\nMemphis 12, Eastern Illinois 1\nTop 6:\nTyler Castro singled, Peyton Wilson scored.\nMemphis 12, Eastern Illinois 2\nBottom 6:\nJack Little\nhomered.\nTrae Cassidy\nhomered.\nMemphis 14, Eastern Illinois 2\nUP NEXT\nMemphis will continue its series against Eastern Illinois on Saturday afternoon at FedExPark Avron Fogelman Field. First pitch is set for 2:05 p.m.\nHOW TO FOLLOW THE TIGERS:\nFor complete information on\u00a0Memphis Tiger Baseball, visit\nwww.GoTigersGo.com\nand follow the team's social media channels on\nTwitter\n,\nInstagram\nand\nFacebook\n."
